In Fortran, since there's no labeled loop, we can use a named loop and exit when needed. So in Fortran, inside the if (score < G) block, we can have:

outer: do i = D-1, 0, -1
   if (.not. btest(bit, i)) then
      do j = 0, p(i) - 1
         score = score + 100 * (i+1)
         solve_num = solve_num + 1
         if (score >= G) then
            exit outer
         end if
      end do
   end if
end do outer

Wait, but in the Java code, the loop is:

for (int i = D - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    if ((bit & (1 << i)) == 0) {
        for (int j = 0; j < p[i] -1; j++) {
            score += 100*(i+1);
            solve_num++;
            if (score >= G) break loop;
        }
    }
} So in Fortran, the outer loop is over i from D-1 downto 0, then check if the bit is not set.
